'''Government spin-off''' is civilian goods which are the result of [[military]] or [[government]]al [[research]]. One prominent example of a type of government spin-off is [[technology]] that has been [[Commercialization|commercialized]] through [[NASA]] [[funding]], research, [[License|licensing]], facilities, or assistance. [[NASA spin-off]] technologies have been produced for over forty years. The [[Internet]] is a specific example of a government spin-off.<ref>{{Cite book|title=International Urban Planning Settings: Lessons of Success|author=Jack Francis Williams|coauthors=Robert John Stimson|publisher=[[Emerald Group Publishing]]|date=2001|page=426|isbn=0762306955|url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=1X0iWczc4Z0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false}}</ref>
